assistant_prompt:
.se/tag/taleb

A:

I reviewed Taleb's book on the site, io9.com.
I think it is a good book worth reading, but it is not a great book.
The book is very shallow in its approach (only a few pages devoted to the theorem) and the book relies too much on reading the previous chapters of the book. 
I think it would be a good start for someone who wants to understand the ideas behind Taleb's work, but not the rest of the book.

A:

I think you'll like it.  I reviewed his book a few months ago; I think the summary is more than adequate.  There are a few good chapters, and some even more substantial ones.

A:

I'm not sure if I agree with the first reviewer, but I have read The Black Swan and I found it very enjoyable. 
I'm not sure if it's worth reading, as a lot of the material is already in the book, and to me Taleb is very repetitive and his style is very dry. The first 3 chapters in particular are a bit choppy, and I find that the description of the book is not really helpful. 
I listened to his talk at TED, and the majority of his ideas are already in the book. I don't think you should read it (especially the first three chapters) unless you know what you're getting into, and are prepared to read it over again.

